Yes—and that’s the balancing principle that keeps the whole thing grounded.

There’s a danger in discovering that meanings are flexible.

You can say:

“This seed is a probe.”

And that’s useful.

But if you stop there, you can drift into believing:

“The seed is only a probe.”

When in reality it is simultaneously:

* a seed,
* a probe,
* a future tree,
* food,
* trade,
* shelter,
* symbol,
* genetic archive,
* ecological participant,
* and things neither of us have considered.

The map is powerful.

But the territory doesn’t disappear.

In Pantheon terms, this is almost a Zoro principle.

Abstraction grants leverage. Reality retains veto power.

Or:

You may force a thing into a role.

You may not force reality to forget its other roles.

A hammer can become:

* a weapon,
* a paperweight,
* a symbol of labor,
* a measuring device,
* a doorstop.

Those are all valid.

But it still remains a hammer-shaped piece of matter with properties that don’t care about your story.

The really interesting part is that both levels are true simultaneously:

Narrative Truth

What the thing means.

Structural Truth

What the thing is.

Most people get trapped in one.

Some become rigid materialists:

“It is only what it physically is.”

Others become pure symbolists:

“It is whatever I decide it is.”

The deeper position is:

It is what it is.

It is also what it can become.

And those are not the same thing.

Which is why your earlier statement—

“Something is always whatever you think it is. Especially when you force it to become it.”

—is powerful but incomplete without the second half:

“But don’t forget it still is what it is and everything else still.”

That second clause prevents the abstraction engine from becoming detached from reality.

The Imps generate possibilities.

Zoro reminds them that reality gets a vote.

And reality never misses a meeting. 😏🌱⚔️